Red-Black Tree:-
A Red-Black Tree is a self-balancing Binary Search Tree (BST) in which every node is assigned a color (Red or Black).
It maintains a set of balancing rules so that the tree height remains approximately balanced after insertions and deletions.
Because of this, search, insert, and delete operations are performed in O(log n) time.

=>How It Works (Theory)
->A Red-Black Tree follows all Binary Search Tree rules:
   Left child < Parent
   Right child > Parent
->Each node is assigned either Red or Black color.
->When a new element is inserted, it is initially added as a Red node.
->After insertion, the tree checks whether any Red-Black rules are violated:
  Root must be Black.
  Two consecutive Red nodes are not allowed.
  Every path from root to leaf must contain the same number of Black nodes.
->If a rule is violated, the tree performs:
  Recoloring (changing node colors), or
  Rotations (left/right rotations)
->These adjustments keep the tree balanced and prevent it from becoming skewed like a linked list.

